article.description: Vanderbilt has mastered the Nashville non-conference portion of its schedule.
article.headline: Commodores 10-0 for first time in school history
article.story: NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Vanderbilt knows it will be remembered by how it finishes the season. Still, the Commodores (No. 24 ESPN/USA Today, No. 22 AP) are off to a near-record start. Matt Freije scored 15 points and Vanderbilt matched its best start in 43 years with an 85-59 victory over Lehigh on Tuesday night. Vanderbilt is 10-0 for the fourth time in school history and is one win short of the school-record for straight wins to open the 1960-61 season. Vanderbilt will have a chance to tie that mark Saturday when it plays at TCU. "The first half of the season is over and the most important part is right upon us," Freije said. "It is good to play well in the first half of the season, but it is better how you finish. That will be what defines our season." Julian Terrell had 14 points and seven rebounds and Scott Hundley had nine points, five rebounds and five assists for Vanderbilt. Freshman Dan Cage had 11 points off the bench as Vanderbilt recorded its 10th straight win by double digits. Vanderbilt's average margin of victory during its winning streak is 21.2 points. "We're capable of playing better, but all in all it was a good performance," said coach Kevin Stallings, who is 44-2 in non-conference home games in five years at Vanderbilt. Vanderbilt shot a season-high 52 percent from 3-point range, (11-of-21). The Commodores outrebounded Lehigh 39-30 and did not allow an offensive rebound in the first half. Reserve Jose Olivero, Lehigh's leading scorer, led the Mountain Hawks (6-5) with 18 points, 16 in the second half. Nick Monserez added 10 points and Austen Rowland had eight points and seven assists. Lehigh lost its second straight game after putting together a five-game winning streak. "Vanderbilt is a terrific team and certainly deserving of a Top 25 ranking," Lehigh coach Billy Taylor said. "They share the ball and have a star player in Freije. We lacked passion, and that disappoints me because we haven't played like that all year." The offensive highlight for Vanderbilt came with 7:50 to play when Cage threw a no-look, over-the-head pass to Terrell for a dunk, stretching the lead to 70-45. "I've only thrown one pass like that in my life and that was in practice a few weeks ago," Cage said. Vanderbilt went on an 8-3 run to close the first half, then scored the first nine points of the second half to take a 48-27 lead on a 3 by Freije. Lehigh answered with eight straight points before consecutive 3-pointers by David Przybyszewski and Russell Lakey gave Vanderbilt a 54-35 lead. Jason Holwerda tipped in a miss by Mario Moore just before the halftime buzzer to give Vanderbilt a 39-27 lead. Vanderbilt suffered through one of its worst offensive stretches of the season early in the first half, going scoreless for 5:20 as Lehigh put together a 6-0 run to cut the lead to 14-11. Moore snapped the string with a 3-pointer. Freije missed the final 5:36 of the first half after slightly twisting his left ankle, but he returned to start the second half and showed no ill effects the rest of the game.
